Find an antiderivative of $1/(x^2 - 2x-3)$.


We again just let `SymPy` do the work. A partial fraction decomposition is given by:

::: {.cell execution_count=14}
``` {.julia .cell-code}
ùíí =  (x^2 - 2x - 3)
apart(1/ùíí)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=15}
```{=html}
<span class="math-left-align" style="padding-left: 4px; width:0; float:left;"> 
\[
- \frac{1}{4 \left(x + 1\right)} + \frac{1}{4 \left(x - 3\right)}
\]
</span>
```
:::
:::


We see what should yield two logarithmic terms:

::: {.cell execution_count=15}
``` {.julia .cell-code}
integrate(1/ùíí, x)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=16}
